╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  SHIP'S ARCHIVE: Regular Expressions                          ║
║  Classification: Concept                                      ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─ ORIGIN STORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  The concept began in 1951 when mathematician Stephen Kleene  │
│  formalized "regular languages" to describe patterns. Ken     │
│  Thompson brought regex to practical computing in 1968,       │
│  implementing pattern matching in the QED editor. He used     │
│  just-in-time compilation to make it fast - a technique now   │
│  common in modern software. Thompson later added regex to     │
│  ed and grep, making it a cornerstone of Unix text processing.│
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ MENTAL MODEL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  A regex is a PATTERN that describes a set of strings:        │
│                                                                │
│    Pattern: cat                                                │
│    Matches: "cat" "catalog" "scat"                            │
│                                                                │
│    Pattern: ^cat                                               │
│    Matches: "cat" "catalog" (only at START of line)           │
│                                                                │
│  Core building blocks:                                         │
│                                                                │
│    .       any single character     (c.t → cat, cot, cut)     │
│    *       zero or more of previous (ca*t → ct, cat, caat)    │
│    +       one or more of previous  (ca+t → cat, caat)        │
│    ?       zero or one of previous  (colou?r → color, colour) │
│    ^       start of line            (^Error → lines starting) │
│    $       end of line              (end$ → lines ending)     │
│    [abc]   any char in set          ([aeiou] → any vowel)     │
│    [^abc]  any char NOT in set      ([^0-9] → non-digit)      │
│    \       escape special chars     (\. → literal dot)        │
│                                                                │
│  Examples:                                                     │
│    ^[0-9]+$         → lines containing only numbers           │
│    \.txt$           → strings ending in .txt                  │
│    [A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*  → valid variable names            │
│                                                                │
│  BRE vs ERE:                                                   │
│    Basic (grep):    escape +, ?, |, (, ) to use them          │
│    Extended (grep -E, egrep): use them directly               │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ CONNECTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  • Used in: grep, sed, awk, find, vim, perl                   │
│  • Alternatives: literal strings (simpler), glob patterns     │
│  • Builds toward: Text processing mastery, programming        │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ ARIA'S INSIGHT ───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  "Start simple. Most real-world regex needs are basic:        │
│  'grep ERROR' for literal text, 'grep '^2024' for lines       │
│  starting with 2024. Build complexity only when needed.       │
│  And use regex101.com to test patterns interactively -        │
│  it explains what each part does."                            │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
